                        </a></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" id="actofsettlement_sng_1" hclass="sense" htag="li"><span class="sensetop" htag="span" hclass="sensetop"><span class="dis-g"><span class="wrap">(</span><span class="dtxt">in Britain</span><span class="wrap">)</span></span></span> <span class="def" hclass="def" htag="span">an <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/act-of-parliament" title="Act of Parliament definition"><span class="ndv">Act of Parliament</span></a> in 1701, saying that the children of <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/james-i#james_i_topg_1" title="James I's definition"><span class="ndv">James I's</span></a> <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/granddaughter" title="granddaughter definition"><span class="ndv">granddaughter</span></a> Sophia would be the future kings and queens. The government made this law because the king at that time, <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/william-iii" title="William III definition"><span class="ndv">William III</span></a>, had no children, and they wanted to stop the Catholic<a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/the-house-of-stuart" title="Stuarts definition"><span class="ndv">Stuarts</span></a> from becoming kings and queens. Sophia was a Protestant. She was married to the Elector <span class="gloss" hclass="gloss" htag="span">(= a type of prince)</span> of Hanover. Their son became King <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/george-i" title="George I definition"><span class="ndv">George I</span></a>, the first king of the <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/the-house-of-hanover" title="House of Hanover definition"><span class="ndv">House of Hanover</span></a>.</span>    <div id="ring-links-box">
